    <bf:originDate>1913-2008</bf:originDate>
    <bf:originDate>(bulk 1950-2008)</bf:originDate>
    <bf:title>
      <bf:Title>
	<bf:mainTitle>William E. Odom papers</bf:mainTitle>
      </bf:Title>
    </bf:title>
    <bf:collectionArrangement>
      <bf:CollectionArrangement>
	<bf:collectionOrganization>Arranged in two parts composed of nineteen series</bf:collectionOrganization>
      </bf:CollectionArrangement>
    </bf:collectionArrangement>
    <bf:collectionArrangement>
      <bf:CollectionArrangement>
	<bf:collectionOrganization>Part I arranged in eleven series. Series 1: National Security Affairs Military Assistant, 1977-1981; Series 2: Assistant Chief of Staff for Intelligence, 1932-1985; Series 3: National Security Agency, 1985-1989; Series 4: Hudson Institute, 1989-1990; Series 5: Speeches and Writings File, 1975-1987; Series 6: Miscellany, 1972-1989; Series 7: Addition, 1918-1992; Series 8: Formerly Classifed, 1977-1982; Series 9: Oversize, 1985-1988; Series 10: Classified, 1972-1989; and Series 11: Top Secret, 1979-1989.</bf:collectionOrganization>
      </bf:CollectionArrangement>
    </bf:collectionArrangement>
    <bf:collectionArrangement>
      <bf:CollectionArrangement>
	<bf:collectionOrganization>Part II arranged in eight series. Series 1: Personal File, 1913-2009; Series 2: Office File, 1974-2008; Series 3: Speeches and Writings, 1962-2008; Series 4: Subject File, 1906-2008; Series 5: Photographs, 1933-2004; Series 6: Digital Files, 1988-2008; Series 76: Classified, 1972-1985; and Series 8: Oversize, 1954-2004; and Series 8: Digital Files, 1988-2008.</bf:collectionOrganization>
      </bf:CollectionArrangement>
    </bf:collectionArrangement>
    <bf:summary>
      <bf:Summary>
	<rdfs:label>Correspondence, memoranda, speeches, writings, logbooks, subject files, scrapbooks, printed matter, photographs, and other papers pertaining primarily to Odom's military career, particularly his service as military assistant to the assistant to the president for national security affairs, Zbigniew K. Brzezinski (1977-1981); as U.S. Army assistant chief of staff for intelligence (1981-1985); and as director of the National Security Agency (1985-1988) as well as his work as an authority on national security policy and the Soviet Union in the years following his retirement from the U.S. Army.</rdfs:label>
      </bf:Summary>
    </bf:summary>
    <bf:summary>
      <bf:Summary>
	<rdfs:label>Part I includes Odom's notes from meetings of the National Security Council (NSC) and the NSC Special Coordination Committee concerning arms control policy and the Strategic Arms Limitation Talks II; government operations during military and other crises; hijackings, terrorism, and the Iran Hostage Crisis; relations between the U.S. and the Middle East; the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan; U.S. and Soviet foreign relations and related strategic defense policy; and other issues pertaining to national security. Also includes material pertaining to Odom's role in smuggling Aleksandr Isaevich Solzhenit︠s︡yn's papers out of the Soviet Union, several letters from Solzhenit︠s︡yn to Odom, and photocopies of Solzhenit︠s︡yn's passports, medals, and personal documents. Other subjects include the administration of President Jimmy Carter; defense policy and the writings of Samuel P. Huntington on strategic relationships; education of military officers in the U.S.; training in intelligence-gathering methods and the role of intelligence in the armed forces and international affairs; military strategy; structure of the U.S. military; and Soviet military personnel and organization. Correspondents include Anne Legendre Armstrong, Zbigniew Brzezinski, George F. Kennan, Eugene C. Meyer, Edward L. Rowny, John W. Warner, and John Adams Wickham.</rdfs:label>
      </bf:Summary>
    </bf:summary>
    <bf:summary>
      <bf:Summary>
	<rdfs:label>Part II focuses chiefly on Odom's work and activities following his retirement from the U.S. Army in 1988, his early life and military career, and family. Documents his experiences as a cadet at the United States Military Academy, West Point, N.Y., and as a graduate student at Columbia University; his military service in Germany and Vietnam; assignment in the Soviet Union as assistant army attaché at the American Embassy in Moscow; service as U.S Army assistant chief of staff for intelligence and director of the National Security Agency during the Ronald Reagan presidential administration; work as director of national security studies at the Hudson Institute and as educator at Georgetown University, the United States Military Academy, and Yale University; and his personal and professional relationship with Zbigniew Brzezinski. Subjects include the Iran-Contra Affair; Soviet and Russian political affairs, military, and intelligence; the Cold War, dissolution of the Soviet Union, and the post-Cold War era including developments in the former Soviet republics; and the Iraq War, 2003-2011. Includes papers of Robert Dujarric relating to his work at the Hudson Institute, particularly his work with Odom.</rdfs:label>
      </bf:Summary>
    </bf:summary>
